A hitting set is a set of squares such that every possible rectangle covers at least one square in the set. 1. **Identify all possible positions of the rectangle**: - There are 12 possible positions: 6 horizontal and 6 vertical. 2. **Consider the structure of the grid**: - The grid has 9 squares arranged in 3 rows and 3 columns. - Each rectangle covers two adjacent squares either horizontally or vertically. 3. **Find a hitting set**: - A hitting set is a set of squares that intersects with every possible rectangle. - After evaluating various configurations, we find that a set of four squares can cover all possible rectangles. 4. **Verify the hitting set**: - The set of squares \{(1,2), (2,1), (2,2), (3,2)\} covers all horizontal and vertical rectangles: - (1,2) covers horizontal rectangles in row 1 and vertical rectangles in column 2. - (2,1) covers horizontal rectangles in row 2 and vertical rectangles in column 1. - (2,2) covers horizontal rectangles in row 2 and vertical rectangles in column 2. - (3,2) covers horizontal rectangles in row 3 and vertical rectangles in column 2. 5. **Check if a smaller set is possible**: - Trying smaller sets (three squares) results in missing some rectangles, confirming that four squares are necessary. Thus, the minimum number of turns required to ensure finding at least one covered square is \(\boxed{4}\).
